<p>The <b>Bedouin</b>, (from the <a href="/wiki/Arabic_language" title="Arabic language">Arabic</a> <i><span lang="ar-Latn" title="DIN 31635 Arabic" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="ar-Latn">badawī</span></i> (<span lang="ar" xml:lang="ar">بدوي</span>), pl. <i>badū</i>), are predominantly <a href="/wiki/Muslim" title="Muslim">Muslim</a>, desert-dwelling <a href="/wiki/Arab" title="Arab">Arab</a> <a href="/wiki/Nomadic_pastoralist" title="Nomadic pastoralist" class="mw-redirect">nomadic pastoralist</a>, or previously <a href="/wiki/Nomadic" title="Nomadic" class="mw-redirect">nomadic</a> group, found throughout most of the desert belt extending from the Atlantic coast of the <a href="/wiki/Sahara" title="Sahara">Sahara</a> via the <a href="/wiki/Western_Desert_(North_Africa)" title="Western Desert (North Africa)">Western Desert</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sinai_Peninsula" title="Sinai Peninsula">Sinai</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Negev" title="Negev">Negev</a> to the <a href="/wiki/Arabian_Desert" title="Arabian Desert">Arabian Desert</a>. Non-Arab groups as well, notably the <a href="/wiki/Beja_people" title="Beja people">Beja</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Africa" title="Africa">African</a> coast of the <a href="/wiki/Red_Sea" title="Red Sea">Red Sea</a>, are sometimes called Bedouin.</p>
